## Review finding from certified-app-v2-5g6

## Problem
In `src/app/api/xrpc/[...method]/route.ts`, when `client.restore(did)` fails because the OAuth session is expired or revoked, the error is caught by the outer try/catch. The error from `NodeOAuthClient.restore()` does not have a `.status` or `.statusCode` property, so the error handler defaults to HTTP 500:

```typescript
} catch (err: unknown) {
  const error = err as { status?: number; statusCode?: number; message?: string }
  const status = error?.status ?? error?.statusCode ?? 500  // ← defaults to 500
  const message = error?.message ?? "Internal server error"
  return NextResponse.json({ error: message }, { status })
}
```

Client-side code (e.g., `profile.ts`) only checks for 400/404 to return null; a 500 from an expired session propagates as an unhandled error to the user instead of triggering re-authentication.

## Fix
Detect session-restore failures specifically and return 401. One approach: catch `client.restore()` separately from the XRPC call:

```typescript
let oauthSession
try {
  oauthSession = await client.restore(did)
} catch {
  await deleteSession()  // clean up stale cookie
  return NextResponse.json({ error: "Session expired" }, { status: 401 })
}
const agent = new Agent(oauthSession)
// ... rest of handler
```

Client-side callers should then treat 401 responses as session-expired and redirect to sign-in.

